{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cacf0d99-c041-4b0b-adbf-0020b4ca2baa","content":"\n\n","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_cQle6lrUdSioVIaRpqsCh8","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Reviewing project files"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_Th9vn28tPGORpwQHiuZlKF","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-97b3760d181947e2acc63853cb635f6b/TestProject.csproj"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-97b3760d181947e2acc63853cb635f6b/TestProject.csproj."},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_Hr7ITOqny6ftDjatlrgzEk","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-97b3760d181947e2acc63853cb635f6b/PipelineTests.cs"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-97b3760d181947e2acc63853cb635f6b/PipelineTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"e5a6736b-3509-4a21-9393-4c17bd3ee2fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change when upgrading from MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0 to MSTest.Sdk/4.1.0, specifically around test discovery with vstest.console. This is a knowledge question about MSTest SDK changes, not a code change request.\n\nLet me look at what's in their project files to understand context, but I likely know the answer already.\n\nStarting with MSTest.Sdk 3.4+, the default test runner changed from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). But actually, let me check the specific version boundaries.\n\nIn MSTest.Sdk 3.4.0+, the `EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatform` property defaulted to `true`, meaning projects using MSTest.Sdk would use Microsoft.Testing.Platform by default rather than VSTest. However, there was a more significant change: in MSTest.Sdk 3.x, you could still use `<EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatform>false</EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatform>` to opt back into VSTest.\n\n\nThe real breaking change in version 4.x is that VSTest runner support was completely removed—Microsoft.Testing.Platform is now the only supported runner, and the VSTest compatibility layer that existed in 3.x is gone. So when they upgraded, vstest.console can no longer discover tests because the SDK no longer generates the VSTest-compatible test host.\n\nThe solution is either to migrate their CI pipeline to use `dotnet test` instead, which natively supports Microsoft.Testing.Platform, or find a compatibility adapter—though 4.x doesn't provide one. Let me check their project files to see what they're actually working with.","outputTokens":671},"id":"95e46bb2-1a97-4f12-9fd7-87a126ab59be","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:33:16.190Z","parentId":"915b30c4-be3d-40d6-a03b-bca7fb4af974"}
